I"²<h1 id="definition">Definition</h1>
<p>There are multiple definitions of the concept fusion ring in the literature, often with subtle differences. On the AnyonWiki the following definition is used.</p>

<p><strong class="label">Definition</strong>
A <strong>fusion ring</strong> \((R,+,\cdot)\) is a ring with unit \(\psi_1\) for which the following axioms are fulfilled:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The underlying abelian group \((R,+)\) is a free abelian group.</li>
  <li>There exists a finite set \(B = \{\psi_i\}_{i \in I} \subset R\) such that \(\psi_1\in B\) and \(R=\mathbb{Z}B\).</li>
  <li>For all \(i,j \in I\)
    <center>
$$
\psi_i \times \psi_j  = \sum_{k\in I} N_{i,j}^{k}\psi_k, \quad N_{i,j}^{k} \in \mathbb{N}
$$
</center>
  </li>
  <li>There exists an involution \(i  \mapsto i^*\)  such that \(N_{i,j}^{k} = N_{i^*,k}^{j} = N_{k,j^*}^{i}\) (Frobenius reciprocity).</li>
</ul>

<p>Immediate consequences:</p>

<ul>
  <li>The fact that \(\psi_1\) is a unit reformulates as \(N_{i,1}^j = N_{1,i}^j = \delta_i^j\) for all \(i,j \in I\), which reformulates as \(N_{i^*,j}^1 = N_{j,i^*}^1 = \delta_{i,j}\) by Frobenius reciprocity.</li>
  <li>The associativity of the ring reformulates as: for all \(i,j,k \in I\)</li>
</ul>
<center>
$$ \sum_{s \in I} N_{i,j}^s N_{s,k}^t = \sum_{s \in I} N_{j,k}^s N_{i,s}^t$$
</center>

<h1 id="frobenius-perron-dimension">Frobenius-Perron dimension</h1>

<p>The involution \(*\) provides a \(*\)-algebra structure on \(\mathbb{C}B\), given by \(\psi_i^* =  \psi_{i^*}\).</p>

<p><strong class="label">theorem</strong>
<em>(Frobenius-Perron theorem)</em>: there is a unique \(*\)-homomorphism \(d: \mathbb{C}B \to  \mathbb{C}\), with \(d(P) \subset \mathbb{R}_{&gt;0}\).</p>

<p>The number \(d(\psi_i)\) is called the <strong>Frobenius-Perron dimension</strong> of \(\psi_i\), and is noted \(\mathrm{FPdim}(\psi_i)\). The Frobenius-Perron dimension of \(R\) is the number \(\mathrm{FPdim}(R):= \sum_i \mathrm{FPdim}(\psi_i)^2\).</p>
